NYC Socrata Portal Analyis¶

This notebook examines some meta-statistics on the datasets on the NYC Socrata portal. It uses a handful of functions from the socrata-reducer library, written for this purpose.

Part I: Defining Datasets¶

Socrata¶

Socrata is a late-stage privately held startup (which may go to IPO any day now) which maintains the Socrata Portal, an interface for hosting open data on the web. The New York City Open Data Portal runs off of a Socrata instance, as do many others; in fact I would go so far as to say that Socrata has a dominent lead in both market and mind share amongst open data practitioners and offices in the United States (for a survey of all of them, check out http://opendatainception.io/).

Endpoints and the Portal/Catalog¶

An endpoint is any unique URI hash hosted by Socrata. This includes all of the datasets we host as well as a large variety of other static resources—things like charts, external links, etcetera. Basically endpoints are "everything", insofar as everything is searchable. The set of all endpoints on an open data portal is known within Socrata as a catalog; here we tend to refer to it as a portal.

This Socrata support article states the following endpoint types:

The dataset catalog is typically the first thing you see on a Socrata site, so what does everything mean on the catalog page?

[...]

Datasets: These are datasets uploaded into the Socrata platform.

External Datasets: links to datasets stored elsewhere on the web.

Files and Documents: downloadable files such as PDFs or Word documents

Filtered Views: These are saved filtered Datasets. This is a view of a the type Dataset, and will be linked to the original Dataset through the "More Views" tab.

Charts: Charts such as pie charts and bar charts created from Datasets. These will also be linked to the original Dataset through the "More Views" tab.

Maps: Maps created from geolocation data or geospatial data (shapefile, kml, or kmz file). If it is based on geolocation data, it will also be linked to the original Dataset through the "More Views" tab.

Calendars: Calendars created from Date&Time data in a Dataset. These will be linked to the original Dataset through the "More Views" tab.

Forms: Forms are created from a Dataset, to collect information from users. These will be linked to the original Dataset through the "More Views" tab.

You can count endpoints by spooling queries against the Socrata Catalog API. As of writing there are 8145 of them.

What is a dataset?¶

Within the Socrata UI a dataset is a piece of open data content, uploaded as a delimited file (csv, tbv, xls, etc.), which is converted by Socrata to and is suitable for display using Socrata's most familiar kind of interface, its spreadsheet format. A good example is the NYPD Motor Vehicle Collision dataset (link):

One more count. Every Socrata portal has a Site Analytics page which provides a range of interesting tidbits about the portal (here's New York's). One of the entries on this page is still another data set counter, with still another number attached to it:

In [62]:
Image("NYC Open Data - Site Analytics Dataset Count.png")
Out[62]:

Ok what they hey? I reached out to Socrata for clarification. First, the site analytics page:

The "total datasets" count on the site analytics page includes all published and unpublished tabular datasets created by uploading a data file (e.g. csv, xls,...etc.) and all published and unpublished datasets created by uploading geospatial files including KML / KMZ or shapefiles. These include public as well as private datasets.

Aha! In other words, 2,360 is the number of published or unpublished, public or private, tabular or geospatial data resources on the entire portal. Uh. Some more semantics. Socrata allows individual users to create accounts on an open data portal, and those individual accounts are given the ability to upload their own resources and to manipulate existing ones (by creating derived views, maps, charts, and other somesuch). You can choose whether you want what you upload something publicly or sandbox is privately (here's what Socrata has to say about it). If you want a resource to not only be public, but also part of the main site index, you have to publish it (or, more accurately, have it published by a site administrator; more info here).

Socrata's support website also has a longer article on the subject, which notes, in really small text at the bottom of the page:

In [63]:
Image("Socrata Totals Discrepency Comment.png")
Out[63]:

But the gist of it is simple—tables and geospatial files, site-wide. Got it.

I've already counted datasets (albeit only public, published ones). Is there a way to count geospatial files? The catalog API doesn't seem to provide an obvious way to do it, so I began to worry this isn't even possible. I asked Socrata about it:

No, geospatial datasets are categorized as display type "map", which is the same categorization given to derived map views, so it's not possible to discriminate one from the other through the API.

The combination of publicly published tables and geospatial files (what I consider to be datasets affidavit) is, to the best of my knowledge, the source of the 1500 figure cited on the Open Data Portal banner. But it's also an apparently unverifiable figure outside of Socrata itself (it's technically possible to tell the difference using the UI, but no one is going to go out and do that).

Not to belabor the point, but there's a few more caveats to note. External links (which Socrata refers to as "federated assets"?) to outside resources are not included, but those are easy to get yoursef (they go under type=link in the catalog API). Neither are so-called blobs—zips of things which are distributed in weird formats, like e.g. the Property Valuation and Asessment dataset, which consists of mdb Microsoft Access files (sorry). Finally, there's some weirdness around the Open Data copy of the Department of Finance's ACRIS dataset, which is distributed as several chunks (filters, in Socrata terminology) of a private view—this private view is the only thing which gets counted.

Conclusions¶

  1. Socrata needs to get their act together, agree on one consistent definition of "dataset" (and related terminology), and stick with it. As the platform continues to get more and more complex this problem is only going to get worse.
  2. Socrata needs to release some way of tracking geospatial files as a part of their API. Right now only Socrata itself can tell the difference—very unbecoming of an open data provider.

Part II: Resourcing¶

Socrata does nevertheless have a catalog API, which, in every other respect, seems to be quite good. Chicago's RSocrata client has an interface to it, but I'm a Python programmer, and sodapy is dataset-specific. So I rolled my own, which I may have developed into a full module by the time you read this.

Here are the definitions I use:

  • Endpoint: Any Socrata resource.
  • Dataset: Any tabular or geospatial endpoint on Socrata.
  • Table: A tabular dataset.

Per the first part of this post, I can't get at datasets, so I use tables instead.

Hashes¶

Socrata endpoints are anchored by unique hases at the end of their URIs. h9gi-nx95, for example, points to the NYPD Motor Vehicle collision dataset, equally accessible at https://data.cityofnewyork.us/Public-Safety/NYPD-Motor-Vehicle-Collisions/h9gi-nx95 (its actual URI) and at https://data.cityofnewyork.us/-/-/h9gi-nx95 (a redirect).

If batch processing all datasets somehow is a goal, it's pretty easy to back out the actual dataset points:

In [171]:
endpoint_hashes = pd.Series([d['permalink'].split("/")[-1] for d in portal_content_metadata])
In [6]:
endpoint_hashes.head(5)
Out[6]:
0    ic3t-wcy2
1    xjfq-wh2d
2    jb3k-j3gp
3    8wbx-tsch
4    erm2-nwe9
dtype: object

These are all you need to build a valid URL. So if, for example, you wanted to programmatically, download all of the datasets on the NYC portal (or some subset thereof), you can throw these at sodapy and digest all of it.

The process for pulling datasets and tables is exactly the same.

def endpoint_categories(data):
    """
    Returns a pd.Series mapping datasets to endpoint categories.
    """
    return pd.Series(list(map(lambda d: d['classification']['domain_category'], data)))

def endpoint_automations(endpoints):
    """
    Returns a pd.Series mapping endpoints to their automation type.
    """
    def get_update_automation_type(endpoint):
        # Get the "domain metadata".
        domain_metadata = endpoint['classification']['domain_metadata']
        # Format example:
        # [{'key': 'Update_Automation', 'value': 'Yes'},
        #  {'key': 'Update_Update-Frequency', 'value': 'Daily'},
        #  {'key': 'Dataset-Information_Agency', 'value': 'Department of Buildings (DOB)'}]
        #
        # If Update_Automation is included it should be *first* entry.
        # But we don't want to just check for that! Because this could change in the future.
        # Instead we need to implement a search strategy.
        # First get all_keys.
        all_keys = [d['key'] for d in domain_metadata]
        # Then try to get the index. This raises a ValueError if it doesn't find anything---return None in that case.
        try:
            # If we didn't fail and return None, pick and return it.
            return domain_metadata[all_keys.index("Update_Automation")]['value']
        except ValueError:
            return None

    return pd.Series(map(get_update_automation_type, endpoints))

Update Frequency¶

In [146]:
def endpoint_update_frequency(endpoints):
    """
    Returns a pd.Series mapping endpoints to their update frequencies.
    """
    def get_update_frequency(endpoint):
        # Get the "domain metadata".
        domain_metadata = endpoint['classification']['domain_metadata']
        # Format example:
        # [{'key': 'Update_Automation', 'value': 'Yes'},
        #  {'key': 'Update_Update-Frequency', 'value': 'Daily'},
        #  {'key': 'Dataset-Information_Agency', 'value': 'Department of Buildings (DOB)'}]
        #
        # First get all_keys.
        all_keys = [d['key'] for d in domain_metadata]
        # Then try to get the index. This raises a ValueError if it doesn't find anything---return None in that case.
        try:
            # If we didn't fail and return None, pick and return it.
            return domain_metadata[all_keys.index("Update_Update-Frequency")]['value']
        except ValueError:
            # Otherwise throw out a None.
            return None

    return pd.Series(list(map(get_update_frequency, endpoints)))

Dataset Ownership¶

Note: this uses information_agency under domain_metadata. There's also resource_attribution under resource, but that seems to be a lot less clean—doing things like substiting NYPD for New York Police Department (NYPD), for example. Though I believe technically these fields are a little different—one is who provided the dataset, one is who made it—but I think it makes little real difference one way or the other.

In [166]:
def endpoint_ownership(endpoints):
    """
    Returns a pd.Series mapping endpoints to their update frequencies.
    """
    def get_endpoint_owner(endpoint):
        # Get the "domain metadata".
        domain_metadata = endpoint['classification']['domain_metadata']
        # Format example:
        # [{'key': 'Update_Automation', 'value': 'Yes'},
        #  {'key': 'Update_Update-Frequency', 'value': 'Daily'},
        #  {'key': 'Dataset-Information_Agency', 'value': 'Department of Buildings (DOB)'}]
        #
        # First get all_keys.
        all_keys = [d['key'] for d in domain_metadata]
        # Then try to get the index. This raises a ValueError if it doesn't find anything---return None in that case.
        try:
            # If we didn't fail and return None, pick and return it.
            return domain_metadata[all_keys.index("Dataset-Information_Agency")]['value']
        except ValueError:
            # Otherwise throw out a None.
            return None

    return pd.Series(list(map(get_endpoint_owner, endpoints)))

def endpoint_creation_dates(endpoints):
    """
    Returns a pd.Series mapping endpoints to their creation times.
    """
    return pd.to_datetime(pd.Series(list(map(lambda d: d['resource']['createdAt'], endpoints))))

Updated-ness¶

In [94]:
def endpoint_update_dates(endpoints):
    """
    Returns a pd.Series mapping endpoints to their update dates.
    """
    return pd.to_datetime(pd.Series(list(map(lambda d: d['resource']['updatedAt'], endpoints))))

Endpoints

In [29]:
# Endpoints by weekly update recentness.

Out[29]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0xfb820f0>
In [32]:
sorted(endpoint_update_dates(endpoints).values)[0]
Out[32]:
numpy.datetime64('2014-09-05T16:57:38.000000000')

Every endpoint was updated at least since September 2014, which seems to imply that there was some software update at around that time which touched and reset this field on every item in the portal. Update history since then is extremely sparse, which makes sense—everything more recent than a few weeks old is static or irregularly updated data. The recent hump is things that are "current".

This plot is more meaningful if we invert. The following plot asks the question: how many datasets were updated in at least the $n$ most recent weeks? This allows us to actually vet the update frequency we are given in the related field against the reality of the Open Data update cycle.

(Note that because of the update issue mentioned above it's not possible to look any further back.)

def endpoint_monthy_page_views(endpoints):
    """
    Returns a pd.Series mapping endpoints to their monthly page views.

    return pd.Series(list(map(lambda srs: srs['resource']['view_count']['page_views_last_month'], endpoints)))

Column names¶

In [123]:
def endpoint_column_names(endpoints):
    """
    Returns a pd.Series mapping endpoints to their update dates.
    """
    all_columns = []
    for endpoint in endpoints:
        all_columns += endpoint['resource']['columns_name']
    return pd.Series(all_columns)
